<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li><a id=3D"org48d8650"></a>Relocatable OCaml Merged<br />
<div class=3D"outline-text-5" id=3D"text-org48d8650">
<p>
In December 2025, the final piece of the <a href=3D"https://www.dra27.uk/bl=
og/platform/2025/12/17/its-merged.html">Relocatable OCaml</a> puzzle was me=
rged, enabling opam to clone switches instead of recompiling them. This fea=
ture will be available in the first alpha release of OCaml 5.5.
</p>

<p>
<b>What Relocatable OCaml Enables:</b>
</p>

<p>
This feature allows the OCaml compiler and its associated tools to be moved=
 to different filesystem locations after installation without breaking func=
tionality. Key benefits include:
</p>

<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li>Binary distributions that work regardless of installation path</li>
<li>Improved flexibility for package managers organizing OCaml installation=
s</li>
<li>Bundling of specific OCaml versions by developer tools without path con=
flicts</li>
<li>Simplified cross-platform distribution</li>
</ul>

<p>
The implementation is the culmination of work by David Allsopp, with review=
 from Samuel Hym, Jonah Beckford, and others. See the <a href=3D"https://di=
scuss.ocaml.org/t/relocatable-ocaml/17253">announcement on Discuss</a> and =
the <a href=3D"https://github.com/ocaml/ocaml/pull/14243">merged PRs</a> (<=
a href=3D"https://github.com/ocaml/ocaml/pull/14244">#14244</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://github.com/ocaml/ocaml/pull/14245">#14245</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
github.com/ocaml/ocaml/pull/14246">#14246</a>, <a href=3D"https://github.co=
m/ocaml/ocaml/pull/14247">#14247</a>) for technical details.
</p>
</div>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
